enth century, the number of Scottish families who still held land in France or made French marriages was slashed by two thirds. Cross-Channel relations were maintained mainly through the extended kin of the Scottish royal family, while the crown of Scotland focused more on promoting relations with England. Ironically, it was precisely this disintegration of kin-based, personal relations between the nobility of these three polities that made it necessary for a formal bond (The Treaty of Paris) to be forged between France and Scotland in 1295, referred to as an "Auld Amitie". M.A. Pollock gained her PhD from the University of St Andrews. She has since taught at St Andrews, the University of Edinburgh, Trinity College, Dublin, and University College Dublin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aNational characteristics. 0aNormans. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnglo-French Nobility.  aAnglo-Scottish Nobility.  aCross-Channel Relations.  aEngland.  aFrance.  aKin-Based Relations.  aKing John.  aKing Philip Augustus.  aNormandy.  aScotland.  aThirteenth Century.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204456740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782044567423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782044567/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles